<h1>The best movies according to Daniel!</h1>
  <h2>My favourite movies on one page!</h2>
  <hr />
  <h2>Star Wars</h2>
  <p>Star Wars isn't perfect.  But it's a space opera that takes us on a thrilling ride. It's got memorable characters, a classic good vs. evil story, and a universe brimming with potential.  The special effects, while dated in the earlier films, hold up surprisingly well, and the sense of adventure is timeless. It's no wonder it's become a pop culture phenomenon.

    Of course, there's always room for debate on favorite characters, movies, or lightsabers. That's part of the fun! What are your favorite aspects of Star Wars?</p>
  <h2>The Lord of the Rings</h2>
  <p>J.R.R. Tolkien's Lord of the Rings dives deep into a rich, hand-crafted fantasy world. Unlike Star Wars' clear-cut heroes and villains, Tolkien creates complex characters with both good and bad sides. The story is an epic struggle for good to triumph over evil, but it feels more grounded and personal than a galactic war. It's a slower burn than Star Wars, but the detailed world-building and character journeys are incredibly rewarding. If you loved the thrill of Star Wars, but are curious about a fantasy adventure with more depth, then Lord of the Rings is definitely worth checking out.</p>
  <h2>Star Trek</h2>
  <p>Whereas Star Wars focuses on a single, Skywalker-centric story, Star Trek offers a vast universe to explore.  Instead of a clear-cut rebellion, Star Trek's crew boldly goes on missions of exploration and diplomacy, encountering new civilizations and tackling moral dilemmas. It's more optimistic about the future, portraying humanity venturing out into space not for war, but for scientific discovery and peaceful coexistence.

    If you enjoy the space battles and alien encounters of Star Wars, Star Trek offers a different kind of adventure. It's less about lightsabers and more about thought-provoking ideas and exploring the potential of humanity.</p>
  
